The '''white-bellied sea eagle''' ('''''Icthyophaga leucogaster'''''), also known as the '''white-breasted sea eagle''', is a large [[Diurnality|diurnal]] [[bird of prey]] in the family [[Accipitridae]]. Originally [[species description|described]] by [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] in 1788, it is closely related to [[Sanford's sea eagle]] of the [[Solomon Islands]], and the two are considered a [[superspecies]]. A distinctive bird, the adult white-bellied sea eagle has a white head, breast, under-wing [[covert (feather)|coverts]] and tail. The upper parts are grey and the black under-wing flight feathers contrast with the white coverts. The tail is short and wedge-shaped as in all [[sea eagle|Haliaeetinae]] [[species]]. Like many raptors, the female is larger than the male, and can measure up to {{convert|90|cm|0|abbr=on}} long with a wingspan of up to {{convert|2.2|m|ft|abbr=on}}, and weigh {{convert|4.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Immature birds have brown [[plumage]], which is gradually replaced by white until the age of five or six years. The call is a loud goose-like honking.

Resident from [[India]] and [[Sri Lanka]] through [[Southeast Asia]] to [[Australia]] on coasts and major waterways, the white-bellied sea eagle breeds and hunts near water, and fish form around half of its diet. Opportunistic, it consumes carrion and a wide variety of animals. Although rated as ''Least Concern'' globally, it has declined in parts of southeast Asia such as Thailand, and southeastern Australia. It is ranked as ''Threatened'' in [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]] and ''Vulnerable'' in [[South Australia]] and [[Tasmania]]. Human disturbance to its habitat is the main threat, both from direct human activity near nests which impacts on breeding success, and from removal of suitable trees for nesting. The white-bellied sea eagle is revered by [[Indigenous Australians|indigenous people]] in many parts of Australia, and is the subject of various folk tales throughout its range.

== Taxonomy ==
The white-bellied sea eagle was [[species description|formally described]] by the German naturalist [[Johann Friedrich Gmelin]] in 1788 under the [[binomial name]] ''Falco leucogaster''.<ref>{{ cite book | last=Gmelin | first=Johann Friedrich | author-link=Johann Friedrich Gmelin| year=1788 | title=Systema naturae per regna tria naturae: secundum classes, ordines, genera, species, cum characteribus, differentiis, synonymis, locis | edition=13th | volume=1, Part 1 | language=Latin | location=Lipsiae [Leipzig] | publisher=Georg. Emanuel. Beer | page=257 | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/2896857 }}</ref> Gmelin based his account on the "white-bellied eagle" that had been described in 1781 by [[John Latham (ornithologist)|John Latham]] from a specimen in the [[Leverian collection]] that had been obtained in February 1780 at [[Panaitan|Princes Island]] off the westernmost cape of [[Java]] during [[Third voyage of James Cook|Captain Cook's last voyage]].<ref>{{ cite book | last=Latham | first=John | author-link=John Latham (ornithologist) | year=1781 | title=A General Synopsis of Birds | volume=1, Part 1 | publisher=Printed for Leigh and Sotheby | location=London | page=33*, No. 7a | url=https://www.biodiversitylibrary.org/page/33727536 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|title= Birds collected during Capt. James Cook's last expedition (1776–1780)|last=Stresemann| first=Erwin| journal=Auk| pages=66–88 [82] | volume = 67 |issue=1 | year=1950 |url=http://sora.unm.edu/node/19760|jstor=4080770| doi=10.2307/4080770}}</ref> It is now one of six eagles placed in the genus ''[[Icthyophaga]]'' that was introduced in 1843 by the French naturalist [[Marie Jules César Savigny]].<ref name=ioc>{{cite web| editor1-last=Gill | editor1-first=Frank | editor1-link=Frank Gill (ornithologist) | editor2-last=Donsker | editor2-first=David | editor3-last=Rasmussen | editor3-first=Pamela | editor3-link=Pamela Rasmussen | date=August 2022 | title=Hoatzin, New World vultures, Secretarybird, raptors | work=IOC World Bird List Version 12.2  | url=https://www.worldbirdnames.org/bow/raptors/| publisher=International Ornithologists' Union | access-date=6 December 2022 }}</ref> Its [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]] is derived from the [[Ancient Greek]] ''leuko-'' 'white',{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=411}} and ''gaster'' 'belly'.{{sfn|Liddell|Scott|1980|p=138}} Its closest relative is the little-known [[Sanford's sea eagle]] of the [[Solomon Islands]]. These form a [[superspecies]], and as is usual in other sea eagle superspecies, one (the white-bellied sea eagle) has a white head, as opposed to the other species' dark head. The bill and eyes are dark, and the [[Talon (anatomy)|talons]] are dark yellow as in all Southern Hemisphere sea eagles. Both these species have at least some dark colouration in their tails, though this may not always be clearly visible in the white-bellied sea eagle. The [[nucleotide]] sequences of the [[cytochrome b]] [[gene]] of the two sea eagles were among those analysed in a 1996 study. Although they differ greatly in appearance and [[ecology]], their [[genetic divergence]] of 0.3% indicates that the ancestors of the two forms might have diverged as recently as 150,000 years ago. The study authors conclude that although the genetic divergence is more consistent with subspecies, the distinctness in appearance and behaviour warrants the two being retained as separate species.{{sfn|Wink|Heidrich|Fentzloff|1996|pp=783–91}}<!-- cites para since last ref --> [[Mitochondrial DNA|Mitochondrial]] sequence of the cytochrome b locus differs very slightly from that of Sanford's sea eagle suggesting a relatively recent divergence after [[New Guinea]]-based white-bellied sea eagles colonised the Solomon Islands.{{sfn|Seibold|Helbig|1996|pp=103–12}}<ref>{{cite book|author1=Wink, Michael  |author2=Sauer-Gurth, H |name-list-style=amp |year=2004| chapter=Phylogenetic relationships in diurnal raptors based on nucleotide sequences of mitochondrial and nuclear marker genes|editor=Chancellor, RD|editor2=B U Meyburg|pages=483–98|title=Raptors Worldwide|publisher=WWGBP|place=Berlin|url=http://abcdef.uni-hd.de/institute/fak14/ipmb/phazb/pubwink/2004/31.2004.pdf}}</ref>

The white-bellied sea eagle's affinities beyond the Sanford's sea eagle are a little less clear; [[Molecular phylogenetics|molecular]] data indicate that it is one of four species of tropical sea eagle (along with the [[African fish eagle]] and the [[Madagascar fish eagle]]), while [[allozyme]] data indicate it might have a closer relationship with the sea eagles of the northern hemisphere.{{sfn|Seibold|Helbig|1996|pp=103–12}}{{sfn|Schreiber|Weitzel|1995|p=}} A further molecular study published in 2005 showed the white-bellied and Sanford's sea eagles to be [[Basal (phylogenetics)|basal]] to the four fish eagles (the two mentioned above plus the two hitherto untested species of the genus ''[[Icthyophaga]]'').{{sfn|Lerner|Mindell|2005|p=}}

As well as white-bellied sea eagle and white-breasted sea eagle, other recorded names include white-bellied fish-hawk, white-eagle,<ref name="Baldwin2010" /> and grey-backed sea eagle.{{sfn|Ferguson-Lees|Christie|2001|p=390}}

== Description ==
[[File:Haliaeetus leucogaster -Bundala National Park, Sri Lanka -flying-8.jpg|thumb|left|Adult flying in [[Bundala National Park]], Sri Lanka, the black flight feathers contrasting with the wing lining clearly visible]]
[[File:Haliaeetus leucogaster -Arignar Anna Zoo, Vandalur, Chennai, India-8a.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Adult in captivity at [[Arignar Anna Zoological Park]], [[Chennai]]]]
The white-bellied sea eagle has a white head, rump and underparts, and dark or slate-grey back and wings. In flight, the black flight [[feathers]] on the [[wing]]s are easily seen when the bird is viewed from below. The large, hooked bill is a leaden blue-grey with a darker tip, and the [[iris (anatomy)|irides]] are dark brown. The [[cere]] is also lead grey. The legs and feet are yellow or grey, with long black talons (claws). Unlike those of eagles of the genus ''[[Aquila (genus)|Aquila]]'', the legs are not feathered. The sexes are similar. Males are {{convert|66|–|80|cm|in|abbr=on}} long and weigh {{convert|1.8|–|3|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. Females are slightly larger, at {{convert|80|–|90|cm|in|abbr=on}} and {{convert|2.5|–|4.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}}. The [[wingspan]] ranges from {{convert|1.78|to|2.2|m|ft|abbr=on}}.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}}<ref>''Raptors of the World'' by Ferguson-Lees, Christie, Franklin, Mead & Burton. Houghton Mifflin (2001), {{ISBN|0-618-12762-3}}.</ref><ref>{{cite book|author=Ali, S.|year=1993|title=The Book of Indian Birds|publisher=Bombay Natural History Society|location=Bombay|isbn=0-19-563731-3}}</ref> A 2004 study on 37 birds from Australia and Papua New Guinea (3&nbsp;°S to 50&nbsp;°S) found that birds could be sexed reliably on size, and that birds from latitudes further south were larger than those from the north.<ref name="ShephardCatterallHughes2004" /> There is no seasonal variation in [[plumage]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=82}} The [[Moulting#Birds|moulting]] pattern of the white-bellied sea eagle is poorly known. It appears to take longer than a year to complete, and can be interrupted and later resumed from the point of interruption.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=92}}

The wings are modified when gliding so that they rise from the body at an angle, but are closer to horizontal further along the wingspan. In silhouette, the comparatively long neck, head and beak stick out from the front almost as far as the tail does behind. For active flight, the white-bellied sea eagle alternates strong deep wing-beats with short periods of gliding.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=82}}<!--cites para -->

[[File:White-bellied Sea Eagle Dobankee Sundarbans West Bengal India 16.12.2014.jpg|thumb|right|A juvenile from [[Sundarbans National Park]], [[West Bengal]], [[India]].]]
A young white-bellied sea eagle in its first year is predominantly brown,{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}} with pale cream-streaked plumage on their head, neck, nape and rump areas.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=82}} The plumage becomes more infiltrated with white until it acquires the complete adult plumage by the fourth or fifth year.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}} The species breeds from around six years of age onwards.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=87}} The lifespan is thought to be around 30 years.<ref name="Biodiv2011" />

The loud goose-like honking call is a familiar sound, particularly during the [[breeding season]]; pairs often honk in unison,{{sfn|Strange|2000|p=73}} and often carry on for some time when perched. The male's call is higher-pitched and more rapid than that of the female. Australian naturalist [[David Fleay]] observed that the call is among the loudest and furthest-carrying of all Australian bird calls, in stark contrast to the relatively quiet calls of the [[wedge-tailed eagle]].{{sfn|Fleay|1948|p=}}<!-- cites previous 2.5 sentences -->

Adult white-bellied sea eagles are unmistakable and unlikely to be confused with any other bird. Immature birds can be confused with wedge-tailed eagles. However, the plumage of the latter is darker, the tail longer, and the legs feathered. They might also be confused with the [[black-breasted buzzard]] (''Hamirostra melanosternon''), but this species is much smaller, has white patches on the wings, and has a more undulating flight.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=83}} <!-- cites para--> In India, the [[Egyptian vulture]] has white plumage, but is smaller and has a whiter back and wings. The white tail of the white-bellied sea eagle in flight distinguishes it from other species of large eagles.{{sfn|Ferguson-Lees|Christie|2001|p=392}} In the Philippines, it can be confused with the [[Philippine eagle]], which can be distinguished by its crest; immature white-bellied sea eagles resemble immature [[grey-headed fish eagle]]s, but can be identified by their more wholly dark brown underparts and flight feathers, and wedge-shaped tail.{{sfn|Kennedy|2000|p=54}}

== Distribution and habitat ==
[[File:Haliaeetus leucogaster -Gippsland, Victoria, Australia-8 (3).jpg|thumb|upright=0.80|right|In [[Gippsland]], Victoria, Australia]]

The white-bellied sea eagle is found regularly from [[Mumbai]] (sometimes north to [[Gujarat]],<ref>{{cite journal|last=Acharya|first=Hari Narayan G |year=1936|title=The Whitebellied Sea-Eagle (''Haliaeetus leucogaster'' Gmelin) in North Gujarat|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=38|issue=4|page=828|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/47603224}}</ref> and in the past in the [[Lakshadweep]] Islands) eastwards in India,{{sfn|Rasmussen|Anderton|2005|p=86}}<ref>{{cite book|author1=Ali, S. |author2=Ripley, S. D. |year=1978|pages=287–89|title=Handbook of the Birds of India and Pakistan: Volume 1|edition=2nd|publisher=Oxford University Press|place=New Delhi, India |isbn=0-19-565506-0}}</ref> Bangladesh, and Sri Lanka in southern Asia, through all of coastal [[Southeast Asia]] including Burma, Thailand, Malaysia, Indonesia, [[Indochina]],{{sfn|Strange|2000|p=73}} the main and offshore islands of the Philippines,{{sfn|Kennedy|2000|p=54}} and southern China including [[Hong Kong]],{{sfn|Strange|2000|p=73}} [[Hainan]] and [[Fuzhou]],{{sfn|Ferguson-Lees|Christie|2001|p=390}} eastwards through [[New Guinea]] and the [[Bismarck Archipelago]],{{sfn|Coates|1985|pp=116–17}} and Australia. In the northern Solomons it is restricted to [[Nissan Island]],{{sfn|Hadden|2004|p=63}} and replaced elsewhere by Sanford's sea eagle.{{sfn|Coates|1985|pp=116–17}} In [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria]], where it is otherwise scarce, it is locally more common at [[Corner Inlet]] and [[Gippsland Lakes]].<ref name="Threatened-Vic" /> Similarly in South Australia, it is most abundant along the north coast of [[Kangaroo Island]].<ref name="KangarooIsland" /> The range extends to the islands of [[Bass Strait]] and [[Tasmania]], and it is thought able to move between the islands and the mainland.{{sfn|Threatened Species Section, DPIW|2006|p=13}} There is one unconfirmed record from [[Lord Howe Island]] and several from New Zealand.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=84}}

They are a common sight in coastal areas, but may also be seen well inland (It is reportedly seen at the Panna Tiger Reserve in central India, nearly {{convert|1000|km|0|abbr=on}} away from the sea shore)<ref name="Sadvi2009" /><ref name="SriramSriramAnand2008" /> The white-bellied sea eagle is generally sedentary and [[Territory (animal)|territorial]], although it may travel long distances. They have been reported travelling upriver to hunt for flying foxes (''[[Pteropus]]''). Populations in inland Australia move around as inland bodies of water appear and then dry up.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=84}}<!-- cites previous two sentences --> In one instance, a pair came to breed at Lake Albacutya in northwestern Victoria after the lake had been empty for 30 years.<ref name="Tarr1962" /> The species is easily disturbed by humans, especially when nesting, and may desert nesting sites as a result. It is found in greater numbers in areas with little or no human impact or interference.<ref name="sprat" /><!-- cites previous 2 sentences -->

== Behaviour ==
[[File:White-bellied fish eagle (Haliaeetus leucogaster) take off composite.jpg|thumb|composite of 4 images showing take off]]

The white-bellied sea eagle is generally territorial; some birds form permanent pairs that inhabit territories throughout the year, while others are nomadic. The species is monogamous, with pairs remaining together until one bird dies, after which the surviving bird quickly seeks a new mate. This can lead to some nest sites being continuously occupied for many years (one site in [[Mallacoota, Victoria|Mallacoota]] was occupied for over fifty years).{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=87}} Immature birds are generally dispersive, with many moving over {{convert|50|km|mi|abbr=on}} away from the area they were raised. One juvenile raised in [[Cowell, South Australia]] was reported {{convert|3000|km|mi|abbr=on}} away at [[Fraser Island]] in Queensland.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}} A study of the species in [[Jervis Bay]] showed increases in the numbers of immature and subadult birds in autumn, although it was unclear whether these were locally fledged or (as was considered more likely) an influx of young birds born and raised elsewhere in Australia.<ref name="SpencerLynch2005" /> Birds are often seen perched high in a tree, or soaring over waterways and adjacent land. They are most commonly encountered singly or in pairs. Small groups of white-bellied sea eagles sometimes gather if there is a plentiful source of food such as a carcass or fish offal on a ship.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=87}} Much of the white-bellied sea eagle's behaviour, particularly breeding, remains poorly known.{{sfn|Debus|2008}}

=== Breeding ===
The breeding season varies according to location—it has been recorded in the dry season in the [[Trans-Fly savanna and grasslands|Trans-Fly region]] and [[Central Province (Papua New Guinea)|Central Province]] of Papua New Guinea,{{sfn|Coates|1985|pp=116–17}} and from June to August in Australia.{{sfn|Beruldsen|2003|p=200}} They are mainly solitary breeders with a few exceptions and are known to form a lifelong pair bond.<ref name =Kirwan>Kirwan, G. M., S. Debus, and C. Hansasuta (2023). White-bellied Sea-Eagle (Icthyophaga leucogaster), version 1.2. In Birds of the World (J. del Hoyo, A. Elliott, J. Sargatal, D. A. Christie, E. de Juana, and P. Pyle, Editors). Cornell Lab of Ornithology, Ithaca, NY, USA. https://doi.org/10.2173/bow.wbseag1.01.2</ref> A pair of white-bellied sea eagles performs skillful displays of flying before copulation: diving, gliding, and chasing each other while calling loudly. They may mirror each other, flying {{convert|2|–|3|m|ft|abbr=on}} apart and copying each other swooping and swerving. A talon-grappling display has been recorded where the pair will fly high before one flips upside down and tries to grapple the other's talons with its own. If successful, the two then plunge cartwheeling before separating as they approach the ground.{{sfn|Lindgren|1972}}{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}}<!-- cite previous four sentences --> This behaviour has also been recorded as an aggressive display against a wedge-tailed eagle.{{sfn|Simmons|Mendelsohn|1993}}

The white-bellied sea eagle usually chooses tall trees or man-made pylons to nest in.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=83}} Often, locations are sought where there is a tall dead tree or high branch with good visibility which can be used as a perch to survey the surrounding area,{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=83}} which is generally a low-lying locale near water with some forest cover.<ref>{{cite journal|last= Thurstans|first=Shaun D.|year=2009|title=Modelling the nesting habitat of the White-bellied Sea Eagle ''Haliaeetus leucogaster'' in Tasmania|journal=Corella|volume=33|issue=3|pages=51–65}}</ref> The perch becomes covered in faeces and pellets and animal remains litter the immediate surrounding area.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=87}} The [[bird nest|nest]] is a large deep bowl constructed of sticks and branches, and lined with such materials as grass or seaweed. Yearly renovations result in nests getting gradually bigger. Nests are generally sited in the forks of large trees overlooking bodies of water.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=89}}<!-- cites previous three sentences --> Old nests of wedge-tailed eagles or [[whistling kite]]s have been renovated and used.<ref name="Threatened-Vic" /> Cliffs are also suitable nesting sites, and on islands nests are sometimes built directly on the ground. A breeding pair, with the male being more active, spends three to six weeks building or renovating the nest before laying eggs.{{sfn|Debus|2008}} Normally a [[clutch (eggs)|clutch]] of two dull, white, oval eggs are laid. Measuring 73×55&nbsp;mm,{{sfn|Beruldsen|2003|p=200}} they are [[Avian incubation|incubated]] over six weeks before hatching. The young are semi-[[altricial]], and covered in white down when they emerge from the egg. Initially, the male brings food and the female feeds the chicks, but both parents feed the chicks as they grow larger. Although two eggs are laid, it is unusual for two young to be reared successfully to [[Fledge|fledging]] (leaving the nest). One egg may be infertile, or the second chick may die in the nest.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=90}}<!-- cites four previous sentences --> If the first clutch is lost, the parents may attempt a second brood.{{sfn|Favaloro|1944|p=}} Nestlings have been recorded fledging when 70 to 80 days old, and remaining around the parents' territory for up to six months or until the following breeding season.{{sfn|Debus|2008}}

=== Feeding ===
[[File:White-bellied Sea Eagle Sundarban West Bengal August 2019.jpg|thumb|right|An adult bird with fish catch from [[Sundarbans National Park|Sundarban]], [[India]].]]
The white-bellied sea eagle is an opportunistic carnivore and consumes a wide variety of animal prey, including [[carrion]].{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}} It often catches a fish by flying low over the water and grasping it in its talons.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}} It prepares for the strike by holding its feet far forward (almost under its chin) and then strikes backward while simultaneously beating its wings to lift upwards. Generally only one foot is used to seize prey.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}}<!-- cites previous two --> The white-bellied sea eagle may also dive at a 45-degree angle from its perch and briefly submerge to catch fish near the water surface.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}} While hunting over water on sunny days, it often flies directly into the sun or at right angles to it, seemingly to avoid casting shadows over the water and hence alerting potential prey.{{sfn|Favaloro|1944|p=}}

[[File:White bellied sea eagle @ madayipara.jpg|right|thumb|Seizing waterborne prey]]

Main fish prey is usually [[catfish]] and [[barramundi]]. and the eagles frequently hunt both small and large specimens, which can exceed {{convert|50|cm|in|abbr=on}}.<ref name = 'Corbett'>Corbett, Laurie, and Tony Hertog. "Diet and breeding of White-bellied Sea-Eagles Haliaeetus leucogaster in subtropical river habitats in the Northern Territory, Australia." Corella 35 (2011): 41-48.</ref> Other important fish prey includes [[needlefish]] and [[wrasses]].<ref name=Smith>Smith, Geoffrey C. "An analysis of prey remnants from Osprey Pandion haliaetus and White-bellied Sea-Eagle Haliaetus leucogaster feeding roosts." Emu - Austral Ornithology 85.3 (1985): 198-200.</ref> Along with osprey, white-bellied sea-eagles sometimes take fish that are toxic, including some [[porcupinefish]] and [[Tetraodontidae]] fish.<ref name=Smith/>

Reptilian prey include [[northern snake-necked turtle]]s (''Macrochelodina rugosa''), [[Arafura file snake]]s (''Acrochordus arafura''), and various [[sea snake]]s.<ref name = 'Corbett'/><ref name="GopiPandav2006" /> Turtles are especially important and the eagles can prey upon turtles of various ages and sizes, up to large adult [[Emydura macquarii|Murray turtles]] (''Emydura macquarii'').<ref name = 'Corbett'/><ref>Debus, Stephen JS. "Biology and diet of the White-bellied Sea-Eagle Haliaeetus leucogaster breeding in northern inland New South Wales." Australian Field Ornithology 25.4 (2008): 165-193.</ref> In one case, the fish eagle attempted to prey on an adult [[Asian water monitor]] (''Varanus salvator''). The eagle attacked the 1.5m long lizard and delivered a fatal injury, though it couldn't carry it due to the lizard's weight.<ref>Iqbal, Muhammad, Christoph Zockler, and Evgeny Syroechkovskiy. "White-bellied Sea-Eagle'Haliaeetus leucogaster' attempting to prey on water monitor 'Varanus salvator'." Australian Field Ornithology 30.4 (2013): 206-209.</ref>

They frequently take waterfowl and seabirds, such as [[little penguin]]s, [[Eurasian coot]]s, and [[shearwater]]s.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}} It is a skilled hunter and will attack seabirds up to the size of a gull, cormorant, gannet, and waterfowl up to the size of [[magpie goose]] (''Anseranas semipalmata'').<ref>Whitehead, P. J. (1999). Aspects of the nesting biology of the magpie goose Anseranas semipalmata: incubation period, hatching synchrony and patterns of nest attendance and defence. Emu - Austral Ornithology, 99(2), 121-134.</ref><ref name =Kirwan/> Aquatic mammals such as [[platypus]] (''Ornithorhynchus anatinus'') and [[rakali]]s (''Hydromys chrysogaster'') are occasionally taken, as well as land mammals such as [[rabbit]]s and [[flying fox]]es.<ref>Debus, S. (2017). Australasian Eagles and Eagle-like Birds. CSIRO publishing.</ref><ref name =Kirwan/><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Mikula|first1=P.|last2=Morelli|first2=F.|last3=Lučan|first3=R. K.|last4=Jones|first4=D. N.|last5=Tryjanowski|first5=P.|year=2016|title=Bats as prey of diurnal birds: a global perspective|journal=Mammal Review|volume=46|issue=3|pages=160–174|doi=10.1111/mam.12060|bibcode=2016MamRv..46..160M |hdl=11104/0259798|hdl-access=free}}</ref> In the [[Bismarck Archipelago]], it has been reported feeding on [[domestic dog]]s, [[cat]]s, and two species of possum, the [[northern common cuscus]] and [[common spotted cuscus]].{{sfn|Heinsohn|2000|pp=245–46}}<ref name="OlsenFuentesRose2006" /> They also feed on carrion such as dead sheep, birds, and fish found along the waterline, as well as raiding fishing nets and following cane harvesters.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}}{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}}<!-- both refs cite previous 2 sentences -->

They harass smaller raptors such as [[swamp harrier]]s, [[whistling kite]]s, [[brahminy kite]]s, and [[osprey]]s, forcing them to drop any food that they are carrying.{{sfn|Hollands|2003|p=196}}{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}} Other birds victimised include [[silver gull|silver]] and [[Pacific gull]]s, [[cormorant]]s and [[Australasian gannet]]s. There is one record of a white-bellied sea eagle seizing a gannet when unsuccessful in obtaining its prey. They may even steal food from their own species, including their mates. The white-bellied sea eagle attacks these birds by striking them with outstretched talons from above or by flying upside down underneath the smaller predator and snatching the prey, all the while screeching shrilly.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}}<!-- cites previous four sentences--> [[Arctocephalus forsteri|Southern fur seals]] have also been targeted for their fish.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dennis|first=Terry E.|author2=Brittain, Ross |year=2006|title=Attempted kleptoparasitism by White-bellied Sea Eagles on fur-seal|journal=South Australian Ornithologist|volume=35|issue=1–2|page=68|url=http://www.birdssa.asn.au/SAOpdf/Volume%2035/2006V35P068.pdf| archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120619100737/http://www.birdssa.asn.au/SAOpdf/Volume%2035/2006V35P068.pdf | archive-date= 19 June 2012 }}</ref>

White-bellied sea eagles feed alone, in pairs, or in family groups. A pair may cooperate to hunt.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}}<!-- cites previous two sentences--> Prey can be eaten while the bird is flying or when it lands on a raised platform such as its nest. The white-bellied sea eagle skins the victim as it eats it.{{sfn|Marchant|Higgins|1993|p=85}}<!-- cites two previous sentences --> It is exceptionally efficient at digesting its food and disgorges only tiny pellets of fragmented bone, fur, and feathers.{{sfn|Fleay|1948|p=}}

A 2006 study of inland bodies of water around Canberra where wedge-tailed eagles and white-bellied sea eagles share territories showed little overlap in the range of prey taken. Wedge-tailed eagles took rabbits, various [[Macropodidae|macropods]], terrestrial birds such as cockatoos and parrots, and various passerines including [[Australian magpie|magpie]]s and [[European starling|starling]]s. White-bellied sea eagles caught fish, water-dwelling reptiles such as the [[eastern long-necked turtle]] and [[Australian water dragon]], and waterbirds such as ducks, [[grebe]]s and [[Eurasian coot|coot]]s. Both species preyed on the [[maned duck]]. Rabbits constituted only a small fraction of the white-bellied sea eagle's diet. Despite nesting near each other, the two species seldom interacted, as the wedge-tailed eagles hunted away from water and the white-bellied sea eagles foraged along the lake shores.<ref name="OlsenFuentesRose2006" /> However, conflict with wedge-tailed eagles over nesting sites in remnant trees has been recorded in Tasmania.<ref name="SpencerLynch2005" />

== Conservation status ==
[[File:White-bellied fish eagle (Haliaeetus leucogaster) juvenile in flight.jpg|thumb|Juvenile in flight]]

The white-bellied sea eagle is listed as being of ''Least Concern'' by the [[IUCN]].{{sfn|IUCN Red List|2012}} There are an estimated 10 thousand to 100 thousand individuals, although there seems to be a decline in numbers. They have become rare in Thailand and some other parts of southeast Asia.{{sfn|Ferguson-Lees|Christie|2001|p=390}} They are relatively abundant in Hong Kong, where the population increased from 39 to 57 birds between 2002 and 2009.<ref name=So2010/> A field study on Kangaroo Island in South Australia showed that nesting pairs in areas of high human disturbance (as defined by clearing of landscape and high human activity) had lower breeding success rates.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Effects of human disturbance on productivity of White-bellied Sea Eagles (''Haliaeetus leucogaster'')|last1=Dennis |first1=Terry E. |last2=McIntosh|first2=Rebecca R. |last3=Shaughnessy |first3=Peter D.|journal=Emu|volume=111|issue=2|pages=179–85|year=2011|doi=10.1071/MU10044|bibcode=2011EmuAO.111..179D |s2cid=56253536 }}</ref> In the [[Eyre Peninsula]] in South Australia, nests have been vacated as human activities have encroached on the eagles' territories.<ref>{{cite journal |last=Dennis |first=Terry E.|year=2004|title=Conservation status of the White-bellied Sea Eagle, osprey and peregrine falcon on western Eyre Peninsula and adjacent offshore islands in South Australia|journal=South Australian Ornithologist|volume=34 |pages=222–28 |url=http://www.birdssa.asn.au/SAOpdf/Volume%2034/2004V34P222.pdf |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20120619100700/http://www.birdssa.asn.au/SAOpdf/Volume%2034/2004V34P222.pdf |archive-date=19 June 2012}}</ref> Elsewhere, the clearing of trees suitable for nesting has seen it largely disappear locally, such as the removal of stands of ''[[Casuarina equisetifolia]]'' in [[Visakhapatnam district]] in [[Andhra Pradesh]] in India.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Sekhar|first=P.S. Raja|author2=Kumar, P. Kanna|author3=Anil, K.|author4=Babu, A. Suresh |year=2004 |title=Sighting of the White-bellied Sea Eagle (''Haliaeetus leucogaster'') in Andhra University Campus, Visakhapatnam, Andhra Pradesh|journal=Zoos' Print Journal|volume=19|issue=5|page=20|url=http://www.zoosprint.org/ZooPrintMagazine/2004/May/20.pdf|access-date=29 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120321092139/http://www.zoosprint.org/ZooPrintMagazine/2004/May/20.pdf|archive-date=21 March 2012}}</ref> In India, nest densities of about one per 4.32&nbsp;km of coastline have been noted in [[Sindhudurg district|Sindhudurg]] and one per 3.57&nbsp;km (45 nests along 161&nbsp;km) in [[Ratnagiri district]] of [[Maharashtra]].<ref name=sindhudurg /><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Katdare|first1=Vishwas|last2=Mone|first2=Ram|year=2003| title=Status of the White-bellied Sea Eagle in Ratnagiri District, Maharashtra|journal=Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society|volume=100|issue=1|pages=113–16|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48602687}}</ref> They also nest on [[Netrani Island]], where about a 100 birds were noted in 1875 (then known as Pigeon Island) by [[Allan Octavian Hume]] who noted that this was perhaps the largest breeding colony of the species.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Stray Feathers|url=https://archive.org/stream/strayfeathersjou41876hume#page/424/mode/1up|year=1876 |author=Hume, A. O. |title=The Laccadives and the west coast.|volume=4|pages=413–483}}</ref> In 2000, the disturbance to the island from torpedo-firing exercises conducted by the Indian navy was noted as a threat.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gadgil, Madhav|author-link=Madhav Gadgil|year=2004|title=Karnataka State of Environment Report and Action Plan: Biodiversity Sector. ENVIS Technical Report No. 16|publisher=ENVIS, CES, IISc, Bangalore|url=http://ces.iisc.ernet.in/hpg/envis/ETR/CES_ETR/etr16.pdf|page=10|access-date=2 July 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090304232316/http://ces.iisc.ernet.in/hpg/envis/ETR/CES_ETR/etr16.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2009}}</ref> Nearly 100 nests have been noted in 2004 on this island.<ref>{{cite journal|author=Madhyastha, N.A.|year=2004 | title=A paradise for White-bellied Sea Eagle: Netrani Island|page=14|volume=44|issue=1|journal=[[Newsletter for Birdwatchers]] |url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B3FJoJNii3LpZjhmMDc0ZGEtMmQyMi00MzZhLTk5MzUtZmYwOTQ4NWI0MjUz&hl=en_US}}</ref>

[[DDT]] was a widely used pesticide in agriculture that was found to have significant adverse effects on wildlife, particularly egg thinning and subsequent breakage in birds of prey. A review of DDT's impact on Australian raptors between 1947 and 1993 found that the average egg-shell thickness had decreased by 6%. This average level of thinning was not thought likely to result in significantly more breakage overall, however individual clutches that had been even thinner might have broken. The white-bellied sea eagle was one of the more affected species, probably due to its feeding in areas heavily treated with pesticide such as swamps. DDT use peaked in 1973, but was no longer approved after 1987 and its use had effectively ceased by 1989.<ref name="Olsen-Emu1993" /><!-- cites para -->

=== Australia ===
The white-bellied sea eagle is listed under the ''marine'' and ''migratory'' categories which give it protected status under Australia's federal [[Environment Protection and Biodiversity Conservation Act 1999]]. As a mainly coastal species, it is vulnerable to [[habitat destruction]] in Australia's increasingly populated and urbanised coastal areas, particularly in the south and east of the country, where it appears to have declined in numbers. However, there may have been an increase in population inland, secondary to the creation of reservoirs, dams and weirs, and the spread of the introduced [[common carp]] (''Cyprinus carpio''). However, it is rare along the [[Murray River]] where it was once common.<ref name="sprat" /><!-- cites previous 3 sentences --> It is also listed as ''Threatened'' under [[Victoria (Australia)|Victoria's]] [[Flora and Fauna Guarantee Act (1988)]], with possibly fewer than 100 breeding pairs remaining in the state.<ref name="Threatened-Vic" /> On the 2007 advisory list of threatened vertebrate fauna in Victoria, the white-bellied sea eagle is listed as ''[[Vulnerable species|vulnerable]]''.<ref name="DSE2007" />

There are fewer than 1000 adult birds in Tasmania, where the species is listed as ''Vulnerable'' under Schedule 3.1 of the Tasmanian [[Threatened Species Protection Act 1995]]. In Tasmania it is threatened by nest disturbance, loss of suitable nesting habitat, shooting, poisoning, trapping, and collision with power lines and wind turbines, as well as entanglement and environmental pollution. Estuaries are a favoured habitat, and these are often subject to environmental disturbance.{{sfn|Threatened Species Section, DPIW|2006|p=14}}<!-- cites previous three sentences --> white-bellied sea eagles have been observed to increase their hunting ranges to include salmon fish farms, but the effect of this on breeding success is unknown.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Wiersma|first=Jason M.|author2=Richardson, Alastair|year=2009|title=Foraging of White-bellied Sea Eagles ('' Haliaeetus leucogaster'') in relation to marine fish farms in Tasmania|journal=Corella|volume=33|issue=3|pages=71–79|url=http://fpop.fpa.tas.gov.au/staffPublications/58791_V33_3_P71_79_Wiersma.pdf|access-date=30 March 2013|archive-date=19 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120619050347/http://fpop.fpa.tas.gov.au/staffPublications/58791_V33_3_P71_79_Wiersma.pdf}}</ref>

== Cultural significance ==
[[File:Haliaeetus leucogaster - Derwent River Estuary.jpg|thumb|Adult flying in Tasmania]]

The white-bellied sea eagle was important to different tribes of indigenous people across Australia. The guardian animal of the [[Wreck Bay Village, Jervis Bay Territory|Wreck Bay]] aboriginal community, it is also the official emblem of the [[Booderee National Park and Botanic Gardens]] in the [[Jervis Bay Territory]]. The community considered localities around Booderee National Park to be connected with it.<ref name="Baldwin2010" /><!-- cites three previous sentences --> A local Sydney name was ''gulbi'', and the bird was the [[totem]] of Colebee, the late 18th century indigenous leader of the [[Cadigal]] people.<ref name="Smith2005NLAnews" /> The white-bellied sea eagle is important to the Mak Mak people of the floodplains to the southwest of [[Darwin, Northern Territory|Darwin]] in the northern Territory, who recognised its connection with "good country". It is their totem and integrally connected to their land.<ref name="Rose1996" /> The term ''Mak Mak'' is their name for both the species and themselves.<ref name="DaiyiRose2002" /> The [[Umbrawarra Gorge Nature Park]] was a [[Dreaming (spirituality)|Dreaming]] site of the bird, in this area known as ''Kuna-ngarrk-ngarrk''.<ref name="LonelyPlanet2003" /> It was similarly symbolic to the Tasmanian indigenous people—''Nairanaa'' was one name used there.{{sfn|Threatened Species Section, DPIW|2006|p=9}}

Known as ''Manulab'' to the people of [[Nissan Island]], the white-bellied sea eagle is considered special and killing it is forbidden. Its calls at night are said to foretell danger, and seeing a group of calling eagles flying overhead is a sign that someone has died.{{sfn|Hadden|2004|p=265}}  Local Malay folk tales tell of the white-bellied sea eagle screaming to warn the shellfish of the turning of tides, and a local name ''burung hamba siput'' translates as "slave of the shellfish".<ref name="Pwee2002" /> Called ''Kaulo'' in the recently extinct [[Aka-Bo language]], the white-bellied sea eagle was held to be the ancestor of all birds in one [[Andaman Islands]] folk tale.{{sfn|Abbi|2010}} On the Maharashtra coast, their name is ''kakan'' and it's call is said to indicate the presence of fish in the sea. They sometimes nest in coconut trees. Owners of the trees destroy the nest to avoid attacks when harvesting the coconuts.<ref name=sindhudurg>{{cite journal| title= Status of White-bellied Sea Eagle Haliaeetus leucogaster in Sindhudurg District, Maharashtra|last1= Katdare|first1= Vishwas|last2= Mone|first2=Ram|last3=Joshi|first3= Pramod| journal= Journal of the Bombay Natural History Society |year= 2004|volume= 101 |issue= 2|pages=314–16|url=https://biodiversitylibrary.org/page/48568242}}</ref>

The white-bellied sea eagle is featured on the $[[Singapore Bird Series currency notes|10,000 Singapore]] note,<ref name="Pwee2002" /> which was introduced into circulation on 1 February 1980.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mas.gov.sg/currency/currency_info/notes/bird_series/Singapore_Circulation_Notes_Bird_Series__10000.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080321030017/http://www.mas.gov.sg/currency/currency_info/notes/bird_series/Singapore_Circulation_Notes_Bird_Series__10000.html|archive-date=2008-03-21|title=Bird Series – $10000 |publisher=Monetary Authority of Singapore |date=31 May 2011|access-date=1 July 2011}}</ref> It is the emblem of the Malaysian state of [[Selangor]].<ref name="Pwee2002" /> Malay magnate [[Loke Wan Tho]] had a {{convert|40|m|ft|adj=mid|-high}} tower built for the sole purpose of observing a white-bellied sea eagle nest in the palace gardens of [[Istana Bukit Serene]] in [[Johor Bahru]].{{sfn|Sanger|1995|p=316}} Taken in February 1949, the resulting photographs appeared in ''[[The Illustrated London News]]'' in 1954.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Photographed at the nest in the top of an enormous jungle tree: Malaya's handsome whitebellied sea eagle|journal=The Illustrated London News|volume=225|issue=6018|page=296|date=21 August 1954|url=https://archive.org/details/sim_illustrated-london-news_1954-08-21_225_6018/page/296/mode/2up}}</ref> The bird is the emblem of the [[Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles]] rugby league team,<ref name="Baldwin2010" /> chosen at the club's inception in 1947.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mwse.com.au/default.aspx?s=history |title=Manly-Warringah Sea Eagles History |author=Fagan, Sean |year=2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110730162643/http://www.mwse.com.au/default.aspx?s=history |archive-date=30 July 2011 }}</ref> From 2010, a nesting pair of white-bellied sea eagles have had their attempts at raising chicks filmed live on "EagleCam", with footage on display at the nearby Birds Australia Discovery Centre in [[Sydney Olympic Park, New South Wales]]. After raising one brood, however, their nest collapsed in February 2011.<ref name="EagleCam" /> The story attracted statewide attention.<ref name="Huxley2010" />

In Thailand, the white-bellied sea eagle is better known as ''Nok ok'' ({{langx|th|นกออก}}, {{IPA|th|nók ok|pron}}). Its story is referenced in [[Jataka tales]], a Buddhist fable, which is Thailand's national religion. Its name Nok ok became the [[Nok Ok|name of]] a ''[[tambon]]'' (subdistrict) in [[Pak Thong Chai district]] of [[Nakhon Ratchasima province]], and in [[Krabi province]], there is a large sculpture of this type of eagle located at intersection near [[Krabi River|Krabi river]] mouth. It is one of the landmarks of [[Krabi|Krabi town]]. In 2005, Nok ok was made into an eponymous supernatural horror [[Thai television soap opera|television drama]] on [[Channel 7 (Thailand)|Channel 7]]. In the drama, Nok ok is a vampire demon bird that resides in a large eagle statue. This drama was very famous and popular along with a theme song, it was very popular. Its chorus became a viral catchphrase among [[Thai people]]. The impact of the drama and theme song made some people believe that Nok ok is really a devil bird.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://amorerana.com/articles/detail/nokoug|language=thai|title=เจาะลึกตำนานพญานกออก นกผีสิง!?|date=2024-06-16|author=กาลนาน|access-date=2024-06-16|work=Amorerana}}</ref>

